"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722546","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-24","<p>HS2 Ltd have made payments of over £5m to following 23 organisations since 2010:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Aecom Ltd</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Atkins Limited</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Automatic Data Processing Ltd</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bryan &amp; Armstrong Ltd</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Capita Property and Infrastructure Ltd</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>CH2M Hill UK</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Communities and Local Government</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Department for Transport</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Environmental Resources Management Limited (ERM)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ernst &amp; Young LLP</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Fujitsu</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lambert Smith Hampton Group Limited</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Michael Page</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Morgan Law Partners LLP</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Morson International</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Mott Macdonald Limited</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>MVA Consultancy Ltd (Systra Ltd)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Network Rail Infrastructure Ltd</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ove Arup &amp; Partners Limited</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Parsons Brinckerhoff Ltd</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Pricewaterhouse Coopers LLP</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Redfern Travel Ltd</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Temple Group Ltd</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>We have based the answer to this question on data held by HS2 Ltd's payments system which supplies details of all payments whether or not a contractual commitment is in place.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-04-24T16:37:13.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722546/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722546/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722546/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-19","High Speed Two","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 2 March 2017 to Question 65186, on High Speed 2, which of the contractors listed in Annex A have been paid total fees of £5 million or more since 2010.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","71380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722547","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Department for Transport does not hold information about the number of cases of possible vehicle registration number plate cloning. However, between 2012 and 2016 the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency issued 233 replacement registration numbers to vehicle keepers who believed that their vehicle registration number may have been cloned.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-04-24T13:01:19.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722547/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722547/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722547/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-19","Vehicle Number Plates: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many cases of vehicle licence plate cloning there have been in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","71342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722548","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-24","<p>At no time have there been personnel at HS2 Ltd on secondment from Bechtel.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-04-24T14:22:37.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722548/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722548/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722548/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-19","High Speed Two: Bechtel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many personnel at HS2 Ltd are or have been at any time on secondment from Bechtel.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","71343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722549","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Department for Transport takes the use of false number plates very seriously. All suppliers of vehicle number plates must, by law, be registered with the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA). Number plate suppliers must keep records of the plates they sell and make these records available for inspection by the police or local authorities. The records must show that number plates have been sold to someone who has proved that they are entitled to display the registration number and provided proof of identity.</p><p> </p><p>If the registered keeper believes that their vehicle’s number plate has been cloned, they should report this to the police who will investigate. Any fines or correspondence the registered keeper receives for offences they are not responsible for should be returned to the issuing authority with an explanation of the circumstances. The registered keeper of a vehicle can also contact the DVLA to request a new registration number if they believe their number plate is being used by another vehicle.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-04-24T14:15:06.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722549/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722549/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722549/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-19","Vehicle Number Plates: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department has taken to protect victims of vehicle licence plate cloning from receiving driving penalties for driving offences they have not committed.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","71341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722550","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-24","<p>No representations have been received from FairFuelUK and no meetings are currently planned.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-04-24T16:43:45.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722550/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722550/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722550/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-19","FairFuelUK","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent representations he has received from FairFuelUK.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","71301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722551","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-26","<p>As part of the overall Survey and Inspection Transformation Programme, the closure of Tyne Marine Office will save the Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA) £88k per annum.</p><p> </p><p>As a direct response to the feedback received during the consultation, the MCA has retained its presence in the north east of England by opening the exam centre in South Tyneside College.</p><p> </p><p>The Maritime and Coastguard Agency will continue to offer customers an appointment based service when appropriate.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-04-26T11:08:29.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722551/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722551/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722551/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-19","Maritime and Coastguard Agency: Port of Tyne","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will restore the counter service in the Tyne marine office.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","71312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722552","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-24","<p>Data on spend on transport infrastructure projects is not available at the level of North Herefordshire. However, figures are available for the West Midlands for total public sector transport spend, as outlined in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p>£million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2014-15<br> outturn</p></td><td><p>2015-16 outturn</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1,434</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1,964</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Current</p></td><td><p>356</p></td><td><p>658</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Capital</p></td><td><p>1,077</p></td><td><p>1,307</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-04-24T12:01:56.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722552/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722552/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722552/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-19","Department for Transport: North Herefordshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much his Department has spent in North Herefordshire constituency since 2015.","false","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","71374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722553","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-24","<p>Chris Gibb’s findings were received by the Department on 30 December 2016. The Department will not be publishing Chris Gibb’s findings before Parliament prorogues however we intend to publish Chris Gibb’s report in full, with minor redactions to protect commercially sensitive material, and the Government’s response in due course.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-04-24T16:01:50.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722553/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722553/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722553/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-19","Southern: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answers of 20 January 2017 to Question 60337 and 21 March 2017 to Question 67853, on what date he received the (a) advice and (b) set of recommendations developed from the advice from Chris Gibb; if he will publish all documents received from Chris Gibb in full before Parliament prorogues ahead of the 2017 General Election; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","71377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722554","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-24","<p>I have not had any discussions with the Department for Education on this topic.</p><p> </p><p>Setting local speed limits is a matter for the local highway authority, as they are best placed to determine the speed limits for their areas, based on local knowledge and the views of the community. The Department for Transport (DfT) has issued guidance to help them in the Speed Limit Circular 01/2013 – Setting Local Speed Limits, which is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/setting-local-speed-limits" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/setting-local-speed-limits</a></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-04-24T11:01:38.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722554/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722554/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722554/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-19","Road Traffic Offences: Speed Limits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Education on educating drivers in built-up areas in which schools are located on the level of risk to pedestrians of vehicles travelling at (a) 30mph and (b) 40mph.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","71363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722555","Home Office","false","2017-04-25","<p>It is an operational matter for Chief Constables, working with their Police and Crime Commissioners, to determine how to use available resources according to local priorities.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-04-25T11:44:49.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722555/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722555/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722555/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-04-19","Roads: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she plans to provide funding to police collision investigation units.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","71364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722556","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Government only carries out regular noise assessments at Heathrow, Gatwick and Stansted, which are designated for noise control purposes. These powers to manage aircraft noise are devolved in Scotland and Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p><p>Under European and domestic law, major airports, or other airports which impact on an agglomeration, are required to produce regular noise actions plans which require an assessment of how communities are impacted by noise and an airport’s plans for addressing these impacts. The last round of noise action plans were published in 2013 and can usually be found on airport’s website.</p><p> </p><p>The next round of noise action plans are expected to be published in 2018.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-04-24T16:46:12.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722556/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722556/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722556/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-19","Regional Airports: Noise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the recent effect of noise pollution from international flights at regional airports on neighbourhoods situated near those airports.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","71365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722557","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Government believes that the treatment of UK consumers has been unacceptable. Consumers should be compensated for the inconvenience, uncertainty and distress caused by Volkswagen’s actions and for any loss in the value of affected vehicles which may become apparent. I have held several meetings with Volkswagen executives and written to them repeatedly about this matter.</p><p> </p><p>Many consumers are seeking independent legal advice on this issue and we are prepared to provide any reasonable assistance to consumers who seek compensation directly. Therefore, I have met representatives of legal firms preparing civil action against Volkswagen and we are considering their requests for assistance.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-04-24T16:48:52.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722557/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722557/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722557/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-19","Volkswagen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to ensure that consumers affected by the manipulation of car emissions data receive adequate compensation from the manufacturers of those vehicles.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","71366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722558","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-26","<p>The number of Marine Surveyors, full time equivalents, employed at the Maritime and Coastguard Agency as at 31 March 2017 was 107, including five Ensign Surveyors.</p><p> </p><p>For each of the subsequent years, through to 2019/20, the forecast is for 128, including nine Ensign Surveyors.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-04-26T11:04:56.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722558/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722558/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722558/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-19","Maritime and Coastguard Agency: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the number of marine surveyors who will be directly employed by the Maritime and Coastguard Agency in each year from 2016-17 to 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","71292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722559","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Department for Transport convened a roundtable meeting with external stakeholders, including some local authorities, in March 2016 following the withdrawal of my Hon Friend, the Hon member for North Dorset’s (Simon Hoare) Private Member’s Bill, which sought to ban pavement parking nationally. A possible pavement parking ban in the rest of England outside London was discussed. However, it was identified at the roundtable that the major concerns affecting the ability to introduce and enforce a pavement parking prohibition were issues relating to the processing of Traffic Regulation Orders (TROs). We plan to launch a survey in Summer 2017 in order to gather evidence about the current situation, the costs and timescales for processing TROs, and information about options for change.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-04-24T14:35:44.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722559/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722559/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722559/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-19","Parking Offences: Pedestrian Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress has been made on preventing pavement parking since the withdrawal of the Pavement Parking (Protection of Vulnerable Pedestrians) Bill 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","71287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722560","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-26","<p>There has not been, and there is no plan for, a new remote IT system specifically to support Marine Surveyors working remotely for the Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA).</p><p> </p><p>The MCA already provides each surveyor with a laptop, mobile phone and printer to support the undertaking of survey and Port State Control inspections at ports. Surveyors are able to, and have been for some time, working remotely using the existing IT equipment.</p><p> </p><p>However, replacement equipment will be issued across the whole of the MCA from April 2017, in line with an organisation-wide refresh.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-04-26T10:52:31.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722560/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722560/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722560/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-19","Maritime and Coastguard Agency: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the cost of implementing the new remote IT system for the Maritime and Coastguard Agency has been.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","71282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722561","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Government is committed to improving access to rail services for passengers and will support proposals for new stations where these are commercially and operationally viable and deliver the quality service passengers want.</p><p> </p><p>While we aware of the suggestion of reopening the station at Camberwell that closed in 1916, no formal proposal or plans have been received by the Department for Transport.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-04-24T13:08:29.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722561/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722561/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722561/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-19","Camberwell Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to re-open Camberwell Station on the Thameslink Line.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","71273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722562","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-26","<p>No representations have been received from FairFuelUK and no meetings are currently planned.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-04-26T08:20:26.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722562/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722562/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722562/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-19","FairFuelUK","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans to meet FairFuelUK.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","71240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722563","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-24","<p>Details of how much compensation has been paid to Southern and Govia Thameslink Railway (GTR) passengers for years 2009/10 through to 2015/16 can be found through the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/566958/train-operating-companies-passengers-charter-compensation.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/566958/train-operating-companies-passengers-charter-compensation.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>With regards to the steps the Government is taking to provide Southern Rail passengers with information on claiming compensation, GTR are contractually obligated to use all reasonable endeavours to make passengers aware of their right to claim compensation through a wide range of measures.</p><p> </p><p>The number of eligible passengers claiming compensation has almost trebled over the past 3 years – up from 12% in 2013 to 35% this year.</p><p> </p><p>This year the Government rolled out enhanced delay repay measures for GTR passengers that allow them to claim compensation when their train is 15 minutes late.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s full response on making claiming compensation easier can be found through the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/government-moves-to-make-rail-claiming-compensation-easier" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/government-moves-to-make-rail-claiming-compensation-easier</a></p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-04-24T13:24:23.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722563/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722563/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722563/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-19","Southern: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much compensation has been paid to Southern Rail passengers in each of the last seven years; and what steps the Government is taking to provide Southern Rail passengers with information on how to claim compensation for delayed journeys.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","71250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722564","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Department does not hold data on trains arriving late at specific stations.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-04-24T13:34:29.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722564/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722564/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722564/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-19","Railways: Southwark","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what proportion of Govia Thameslink trains have been late arriving at train stations in the London Borough of Southwark in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","71251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722565","Home Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Government recognises that drink driving is a serious threat to road safety and shares the police’s desire to have roadside evidential breath test instruments available for use.</p><p>That is why the Home Office, Department for Transport and the police have been working with manufacturers towards the Type Approval of a new generation of Mobile Evidential Breath Test Instruments (MEBTI) as soon as practicably possible. Type approval is a complex process and relies on the submission by manufacturers of instruments which then perform satisfactorily during testing. The Home Office has no control over these factors.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-04-24T13:49:17.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722565/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722565/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722565/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-04-19","Breathalysers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress is being made by her Department on obtaining Home Office Type Approval for mobile evidential breath testing equipment.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","71245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722566","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-24","<p>This policy affects Universal Credit recipients only, not Housing Benefit recipients.</p><p> </p><p>There is a wide range of exemptions from this policy which will ensure that vulnerable people are protected. As the policy will only apply to those who have no impediment to a return to the parental home I do not anticipate that there will be any impact on the levels of homelessness.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-04-24T14:59:03.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722566/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722566/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722566/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-04-19","Homelessness: Coventry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of changes to housing benefit for unemployed 18 to 21-year olds on levels of homelessness in (a) Coventry South constituency and (b) the City of Coventry.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","71265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722567","Women and Equalities","false","2017-04-27","<p>All grants are made in accordance with the Government’s Grants Standards (<a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/grants-standards" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/grants-standards</a>) which are designed to ensure taxpayers’ money, awarded through government grants, is properly agreed and spent. The standards provide a transparent and robust way to manage the government grants process.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-04-27T09:06:18.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722567/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722567/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722567/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-04-19","Pregnancy: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what the Government's policy is on whether organisations which lobby against a woman's right to choose whether to continue with a pregnancy should be permitted to receive public funds.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","71288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722568","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Department of Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS) administers the Tampon Tax Fund. Since the announcement in late March of the 70 projects that successfully applied to the Tampon Tax Fund this year, DCMS has received correspondence from the public and letters from Members of Parliament regarding matters raised with them by their constituents, as well as a petition organised by the group 38 Degrees. This correspondence also included letters supporting the award of the grant.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2017-04-26T16:43:40.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722568/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722568/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722568/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-04-19","LIFE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether she received representations on concerns relating to the application made by the charity, Life for funding from the Tampon Tax Fund.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","71346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722569","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-24","<p>BT (and KCom in the Hull area) offer a social tariff for home phone and broadband under EU and domestic legislation. Whilst no specific tariffs are offered by the main energy providers, the Money Advice Service found that people could save money by switching. There has been an improvement in the switching infrastructure to help customers and Work Coaches are now able to direct claimants to switching services through the new “managing you money” leaflet.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-04-24T15:55:29.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722569/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722569/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722569/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-04-19","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Minister for Disabled People, Health and Work of 18 April 2017, Official Report, columns 650-51, which suppliers of (a) telecoms and (b) energy offer social tariffs to claimants of employment and support allowance in the work-related activity group.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","71359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722570","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-24","<p>The latest available data on the outcome of the initial decision on each disability living allowance reassessment to personal independence payment (PIP) can be found in table 8B of the statistical tables released in December 2016 here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/576641/pip-official-statistics-dla-to-pip-reassessment-outcomes-october-2016.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/576641/pip-official-statistics-dla-to-pip-reassessment-outcomes-october-2016.ods</a></p><p> </p><p>The information requested for cases following a mandatory reconsideration or an appeal is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-04-24T15:49:26.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722570/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722570/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722570/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-04-19","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of disability living allowance reassessments, including cases following either a mandatory reconsideration or an appeal, have resulted in (a) a lower or (b) no award of personal independence payment.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","71360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722571","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-24","<p>The information requested on the number of individuals in receipt of Carer’s Allowance by parliamentary constituency is published and available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-04-24T11:37:23.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722571/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722571/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722571/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-04-19","Carer's Allowance: West Bromwich East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in West Bromwich East constituency receive carer's allowance.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","71285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722572","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-26","<p>DWP has not made an assessment specifically looking at the effect of paying Housing Benefit directly to tenants and their ability to secure accommodation in the private rented sector. The Government believes that direct payment of Housing Benefit to claimants is an important consideration in encouraging people to manage their own budget in the same way as other households, particularly where it may help claimants when they move in work.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-04-26T16:10:11.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722572/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722572/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722572/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-04-19","Housing Benefit: Private Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of paying housing benefit directly to tenants on their ability to secure accommodation in the private rented sector.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","71310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722573","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Government believes that direct payment of Housing Benefit to claimants is an important consideration in encouraging people to manage their own budget in the same way as other households, particularly where it may help claimants when they move in work.</p><p> </p><p>Direct payment of Housing Benefit to tenants was introduced nationally in the private rented sector from 2008 as part of the Local Housing Allowance scheme. Whilst the majority of Housing Benefit claimants are paid directly, there is still provision for direct payments to be made to landlords in certain circumstances. The number of tenants in receipt of Housing Benefit in the private rented sector is available on <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/jsf/login.xhtml" target="_blank">DWP Stat-Xplore</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-04-26T16:20:45.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722573/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722573/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722573/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-04-19","Housing Benefit: Private Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of number of tenants in receipt of housing benefit in the private rented sector (a) prior to housing benefit being paid directly to the tenant and (b) since housing benefit has been paid directly to the tenant.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","71311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722574","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-26","<p>DWP does not collect data on rent arrears. The Government believes that direct payment of Housing Benefit to claimants is an important consideration in encouraging people to manage their own budget in the same way as other households, particularly where it may help claimants when they move into work.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-04-26T16:12:20.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722574/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722574/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722574/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-04-19","Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the level of rent arrears in (a) public and (b) private sector accommodation since housing benefit has been paid directly to tenants.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","71238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722575","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-24","<p>Latest Households Below Average Income (HBAI) data on low income rates for children showed an increase of 1 percentage point between 2014/15 and 2015/16 on a relative basis (for both before and after housing costs), whereas it was unchanged on an absolute basis.</p><p> </p><p>These estimates are from sample survey data and subject to statistical uncertainty. The increases in relative low income were not statistically significant, which means we cannot say with high confidence the change is a real one, rather than due to having a different sample for this year of the survey. As such, focus should be more on longer-term trends rather than small year-on-year changes.</p><p> </p><p>Full explanations of the trends in low income rates are available in HBAI:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/households-below-average-income-199495-to-201516" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/households-below-average-income-199495-to-201516</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-04-24T16:06:40.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722575/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722575/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722575/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-04-19","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reasons the number of children in relative low-income households increased between 2014-15 and 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","71258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722576","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-24","<p>Latest Households Below Average Income (HBAI) data on low income rates for pensioners showed increases between 2014/15 and 2015/16 on a relative and absolute basis. None of the increases in low income rates were statistically significant, which means we cannot say with high confidence the change is a real one, rather than due to having a different sample for this year of the survey.</p><p>These estimates are from sample survey data and subject to statistical uncertainty. Small changes on a year-to-year basis are particularly subject to these uncertainties and it is therefore difficult to identify causality. As such, focus should be more on longer-term trends rather than small year-on-year changes.</p><p> </p><p>Full explanations of the trends in low income rates are available in HBAI:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/households-below-average-income-199495-to-201516" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/households-below-average-income-199495-to-201516</a></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-04-24T11:00:14.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722576/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722576/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722576/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-04-19","Pensioners: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reasons pensioner poverty increased between 2014-15 and 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","71259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722577","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions does not plan to publish estimates of the operational costs of implementing the benefit cap policy, nor the costs of providing support to capped claimants.</p><p> </p><p>The benefit cap was lowered on the 7th November from £26,000 to £20,000, except in London where it was lowered to £23,000 (a lower cap applies to single adult households).</p><p> </p><p>To help ensure Local Authorities are able to protect the most vulnerable Housing Benefit claimants and to support households adjusting to our welfare reforms, the Government will provide over £800m funding for Discretionary Housing Payments over the next 5 years from 2016/17. Information about this and other measures to ease the transition for families affected by this policy change is included in the latest impact assessment at the link below.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/welfare-reform-and-work-act-impact-assessment-for-the-benefit-cap" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/welfare-reform-and-work-act-impact-assessment-for-the-benefit-cap</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-04-24T13:15:35.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722577/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722577/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722577/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-04-19","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his Department's impact assessment of 25 August 2016 on the lower benefit cap, if he will publish the refined estimates of the operational costs of implementing that cap and of providing support to capped claimants.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","71255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722578","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-26","<p>The attached tables show the amount and proportion of research income earned by each higher education institution (HEI) from the Research Councils and higher education funding bodies across the UK in each of the last three years.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-04-26T09:04:18.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722578/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722578/answer","HE-research-income-71276.xlsx","HE-research-income-71276.xlsx","HE Provider income from RCs & Funding Councils","HE Provider income from RCs & Funding Councils","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722578/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-19","Research: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much government research funding was provided to each higher education institution in each of the last three years; what proportion of all government research funding is provided to such institutions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","71276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722579","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-25","<p>Energy generation is not a qualifying activity for the tax advantaged venture capital schemes, including the Enterprise Investment Scheme (EIS). The purpose of this rule is to ensure that the tax reliefs offered through the schemes are well targeted towards encouraging investment into companies that struggle to access the finance they need to grow. Companies that develop energy generation technology may still qualify for the schemes.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-04-25T10:46:45.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722579/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722579/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722579/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-04-19","Enterprise Investment Scheme: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans to review the effect of the Enterprise Investment Scheme on energy businesses; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","71355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722580","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>Over 1000 small-scale (high or low head) hydro installations have been registered in the Feed-in Tariff scheme since April 2010, comprising 182 megawatts of capacity as of the end of February 2017. The Feed-in Tariff contributed to a doubling* in the number of hydro installations in the UK between 2010 and 2015, though a smaller proportion in terms of capacity, as none of these new sites are above 2MW in size.</p><p><em>*<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/regional-renewable-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/regional-renewable-statistics</a> </em></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-04-24T16:31:17.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722580/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722580/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722580/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-19","Hydroelectric Power: Feed-in Tariffs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect of the feed-in tariff on low head hydro schemes in England; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","71357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722581","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>No final decision has yet been taken by the Members of European Centre for Medium Range Weather Forecasts (ECMWF) on the future location of its supercomputer. We have made clear the UK’s commitment and enduring entitlement to hosting the ECMWF Headquarters.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-04-24T15:14:34.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722581/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722581/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722581/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-19","European Centre for Medium Range Weather Forecasts: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that staff remain in the UK in the light of the European Centre for Medium-range Weather Forecasts supercomputer moving to Italy.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","71381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722582","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-24","<p>I refer the hon Member to the answer I gave to the hon Member for Hornsey and Wood Green on 20/04/17 UIN 70775.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-04-24T13:58:27.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722582/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722582/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722582/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-19","Drugs: Philippines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether he discussed deaths related to the war on drugs in the Philippines at his meeting with the President of the Philippines on 4 April 2017.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","71293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722583","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-04-24","<p>The EU Right to Healthcare is a principle for the development of EU law. It did not create new rights to health care above and beyond what is already provided under national laws and practices. The UK's commitment to universal healthcare, free at the point of delivery, goes well beyond minimum EU requirements.</p><p>The Great Repeal Bill will ensure that there is maximum possible certainty as to the rights and obligations in our law upon leaving the EU. And it will allow for a smooth and orderly exit that provides a secure basis for future changes to our domestic law.</p><p>The Bill will ensure that, wherever possible, the same rules and laws apply on the day after we leave the EU as they did before. This means that the Bill will convert directly-applicable EU law into UK law; it will preserve all the laws we have made in the UK to implement our EU obligations, as well as the rights in the EU treaties that can be relied on directly in court by an individual.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-04-24T16:52:38.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722583/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722583/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722583/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-04-19","Health: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether the fundamental right to health, and the legal obligation to ensure a high level of human protection, as set out in the EU treaties, will be incorporated into UK law as part of the Great Repeal Bill.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","71297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722584","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-04-27","<p>The Great Repeal Bill will ensure that there is maximum possible certainty as to the rights and obligations in our law upon leaving the EU. And it will allow for a smooth and orderly exit that provides a secure basis for future changes to our domestic law.</p><p>The Bill will ensure that, wherever possible, the same rules and laws apply on the day after we leave the EU as they did before. Where rights in the EU treaties can be relied on directly in court by an individual, those rights will continue to be available in UK law under the Great Repeal Bill.</p><p /> <p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-04-27T09:21:18.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722584/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722584/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722584/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-04-19","EU law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 2.11, page 15 of the White Paper, Legislating for the United Kingdom's Withdrawal from the European Union, what the rights are in the EU treaties that can be relied on directly in court by an individual that will continue to be available under UK law after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","71338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722585","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Government’s approach is that the Great Repeal Bill will convert current EU law into domestic law wherever practicable, ensuring a functioning statute book on exit. It is essential that there is a common understanding of what the law means. The Government believes that this is best achieved by providing for continuity in how that law is interpreted before and after exit day. That includes interpretation in light of the general principles of EU law, such as fundamental rights, proportionality and legal certainty.</p><p>After we leave the EU, Parliament will be free to change the law where it decides it is right to do so. The terms of the UK’s future relationship with the EU will be a matter for negotiations.<br><br></p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-04-24T13:47:17.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722585/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722585/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722585/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-04-19","EU law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to page 32, paragraphs A.8 and A.9 of Annex A of the White Paper, Legislating for the United Kingdom's withdrawal from the European Union, which general principles of EU law will continue to apply to the UK in any future relationships with the EU.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","71361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722586","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-04-27","<p>The Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union has regular discussions with Cabinet colleagues on matters relating to the UK exiting the European Union. As the Prime Minister set out in her speech, one of the objectives for the negotiations ahead is to continue practical cooperation with the EU to tackle cross-border crime and to keep our people safe. We want to agree a deep and special partnership taking in both economic and security cooperation to fight terrorism and uphold justice across Europe. The safety of the British public is a top priority and security is enhanced through cooperating with Europe.</p><p>As part of the negotiations, we will discuss with the EU and Member States how best to continue cooperation on a range of issues, including Europol and Eurojust.</p><p><strong><br></strong></p><p><strong><p><p><br></strong></p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","70241","2017-04-27T08:52:46.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722586/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722586/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722586/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-04-19","Eurojust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with his Cabinet colleagues on the UK's participation in Eurojust after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","71376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722587","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-04-27","<p>The precautionary principle has had an important influence on the drafting of EU environmental legislation, which will be incorporated into domestic law through the Great Repeal Bill. The Great Repeal Bill will ensure that the whole body of existing EU environmental legislation continues to have effect in UK law.</p><p>As set out in the white paper, Great Repeal Bill will ensure that, wherever practical and appropriate, the same rules and laws apply on the day after we leave the EU as they did before. This means that the Bill will convert directly-applicable EU law into UK law; it will preserve all the laws we have made in the UK to implement our EU obligations, as well as the rights in the EU treaties that can be relied on directly in court by an individual.</p><p>This legislation is the first step in the Prime Minister’s Plan for Britain. It will allow for a smooth and orderly exit and provide a functioning statute book at the point we leave the EU.</p><p><strong><p><p></strong></p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-04-27T09:23:12.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722587/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722587/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722587/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-04-19","EU law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what plans the Government has to include provision in the planned Great Repeal Bill to transpose the EU precautionary principle into UK law.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","71347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722050","Attorney General","false","2017-04-25","<p>Any member of staff in the Law Officers’ Departments might respond to Freedom of Information requests, depending upon the nature and substance of each individual request and who within the different departments is best placed to answer.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-04-25T14:49:31.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722050/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722050/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722050/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-04-18","Attorney General: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many staff in the Law Officers' Departments respond to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","71035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722051","Cabinet Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>FOI requests may be responded to by any member of staff across the Department, as they are allocated to the most appropriate person to respond depending on the subject of the request.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-04-24T15:38:17.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722051/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722051/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722051/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-04-18","Cabinet Office: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many staff in his Department respond to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","71036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722052","Cabinet Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>Information relating to the recruitment process of the Commissioner Public Appointments can be found in the Public Administration and Constitutional Affairs Select Committee’s Seventh Report of Session 2015–16, link below:</p><p><strong><br> </strong><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/public-administration-and-constitutional-affairs-committee/inquiries/parliament-2015/commissioner-for-public-appointments/" target="_blank"><strong>http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/public-administration-and-constitutional-affairs-committee/inquiries/parliament-2015/commissioner-for-public-appointments/</strong></a></p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","71000 ; 71002 ; 71003","2017-04-24T15:40:26.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722052/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722052/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722052/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-04-18","Public Appointments Commissioner","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, where the post of the current Public Appointments Commissioner was advertised.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","71085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722053","Cabinet Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Government believes that electoral fraud is unacceptable on any level. In December last year, the Government published its response to Sir Eric Pickles’ review of electoral fraud, <em>Securing the ballot</em>.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s response set out the mechanisms by which each of Sir Eric’s recommendations can be implemented, including through primary legislation, secondary legislation, or through changes to guidance.</p><p> </p><p>The Government provides support to Returning Officers, who have responsibility for ensuring the integrity of 2017 polls, and works closely with the Electoral Commission and the National Police Chiefs’ Council, with a view to preventing electoral fraud.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-04-26T11:05:14.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722053/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722053/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722053/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-04-18","Elections: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what analysis his Department has undertaken on susceptibility to electoral fraud of local and national electoral processes.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","71056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722054","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Department of Culture, Media and Sport holds primary responsibility for Artificial Intelligence (AI) policy. DCMS and BEIS jointly support the industry-led review of Artificial Intelligence announced in the Digital Strategy.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-04-24T15:19:50.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722054/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722054/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722054/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-04-18","Artificial Intelligence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, which Government Department holds primary responsibility for policy on artificial intelligence.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","71070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722055","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-24","<p>DCMS publish exports of services figure for the Digital Sector at https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/544789/DCMS_Sectors_Economic_Estimates_2016.xlsx, as part of DCMS Sectors Economic Estimates.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-04-24T15:23:38.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722055/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722055/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722055/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-04-18","Electronic Commerce","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress her Department has made on the gathering of statistics on digital trade; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","71074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722056","Cabinet Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Digital Academy has trained 3,028 civil servants on digital and agile courses from April 2016 to April 2017.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-04-24T15:32:22.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722056/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722056/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722056/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-04-18","Civil Servants: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many civil servants have received training through the Digital Academy since April 2016.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","71075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722057","Cabinet Office","false","2017-04-25","<p>Within Cabinet Office, the Cyber and Government Security Directorate (CGSD) is responsible for ensuring delivery of the National Cyber Security Strategy. At any one time approximately 45 full time equivalent staff in CGSD work directly on cyber security. There have been no consultants employed in cyber security roles within CGSD over the last 5 years. At various times CGSD has employed secondees from the private sector.</p><p> </p><p>There are other roles in Cabinet Office teams which work partially on cyber security as part of broader policy and security issues. Details of exact numbers of roles and responsibilities over the last five years could only be determined at a disproportionate cost.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-04-25T15:07:43.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722057/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722057/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722057/answer","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722057/answer/previousversion/45686","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-04-18","Cabinet Office: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many (a) staff of his Department and (b) consultants have been employed in cyber security roles in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","71076"
