"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722059","Cabinet Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>Information relating to the recruitment process of the Commissioner Public Appointments can be found in the Public Administration and Constitutional Affairs Select Committee’s Seventh Report of Session 2015–16, link below:</p><p><strong><br> </strong><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/public-administration-and-constitutional-affairs-committee/inquiries/parliament-2015/commissioner-for-public-appointments/" target="_blank"><strong>http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/public-administration-and-constitutional-affairs-committee/inquiries/parliament-2015/commissioner-for-public-appointments/</strong></a></p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","71000 ; 71003 ; 71085","2017-04-24T15:40:26.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722059/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722059/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722059/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-04-18","Public Appointments Commissioner","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the number of applicants was for the current position of Public Appointments Commissioner by (a) gender, (b) ethnicity and (c) socio-economic background.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","71002"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722060","Cabinet Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>Information relating to the recruitment process of the Commissioner Public Appointments can be found in the Public Administration and Constitutional Affairs Select Committee’s Seventh Report of Session 2015–16, link below:</p><p><strong><br> </strong><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/public-administration-and-constitutional-affairs-committee/inquiries/parliament-2015/commissioner-for-public-appointments/" target="_blank"><strong>http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/public-administration-and-constitutional-affairs-committee/inquiries/parliament-2015/commissioner-for-public-appointments/</strong></a></p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","71000 ; 71002 ; 71085","2017-04-24T15:40:26.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722060/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722060/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722060/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-04-18","Public Appointments Commissioner","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many applicants there were for the most recent recruitment for the position of Public Appointments Commissioner.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","71003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722061","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Government continues to carry out a significant amount of work to assess the economic and fiscal impacts of leaving the EU, as part of a continuing programme of analytical work covering a range of possible exit scenarios, including sectoral analysis. The location of the European Union’s agencies is a matter for the European Union. As we enter into negotiations, we will work hard to seek the best possible deal for the UK.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-04-24T14:33:30.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722061/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722061/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722061/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-04-18","European Banking Authority and European Medicines Agency: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the tax revenues that will be lost when the European Medicines Agency and the European Banking Authority leave the UK.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","71010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722062","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-24","<p>The government has considered the impact on all benefits and tax credits rates that are included in the four year uprating freeze. The government has published an impact assessment at: http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006C.pdf</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-04-24T13:57:09.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722062/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722062/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-04-18","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if his Department will make an assessment of the effect of freezing rates of child benefit and child tax credit on children living in poverty in Kilmarnock and Loudoun constituency.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","71014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722063","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-24","<p>Employers do not need to pay their employees by BACS (Direct Credit), but where they do, the BACS hash enables HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) to automatically verify that the payment amount reported by the employer is the same as the payment received in the individual’s bank account.</p><p> </p><p>Where HMRC receives a hash from an employer, HMRC share whether or not this has matched with DWP who use this information to help validate Universal Credit claims.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-04-24T11:43:20.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722063/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722063/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-04-18","PAYE","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what use HM Revenue and Customs makes of BACS hashing to check the accuracy of employers' submissions through real-time information of employees' pay.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","71092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722064","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-24","<p>HM Revenue and Customs conducted high level People Impact and Equality Assessments to inform its planning and has already published a summary to its staff. The Department is considering future publication plans.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-04-24T11:55:04.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722064/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722064/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722064/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-04-18","Revenue and Customs: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans for the equality impact assessment for the Building Our Future proposals to be published.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","71095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722065","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-24","<p>HM Revenue and Customs does not have any plans to apply for accreditation as a Living Wage employer for either directly employed staff, or third party contracted staff.</p><p> </p><p>As a statutory requirement, HM Revenue and Customs ensures all staff employed directly or through third party contract receive at least the National Living Wage, which was introduced in April 2016.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-04-24T11:53:28.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722065/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722065/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722065/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-04-18","Revenue and Customs: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans there are for HM Revenue and Customs to sign up to be a living wage employer.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","71096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722066","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-24","<p>All officials in the department have an ongoing responsibility for resolving Freedom of Information requests which fall within their policy area or remit. Officials are supported by a team of eight full time equivalents in the Information Rights Unit whose primary role is to oversee, coordinate and ensure the department’s obligations under the Freedom of Information Act are fulfilled.</p><p> </p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-04-24T15:31:11.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722066/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722066/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722066/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-04-18","Treasury: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many staff in his Department respond to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","71052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722067","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-24","<p>The administration of the tax system, including where appropriate the repayment of tax or duties, is a matter for HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC). It would not be appropriate for Treasury Ministers to become involved in specific cases.</p><p>Treasury Ministers do not generally consider the implications of individual court cases unless, on advice from HMRC, such cases have wide and significant implications for the UK tax system. No such advice has been received from HMRC in this instance.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-04-24T12:05:00.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722067/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722067/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722067/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-04-18","Employee Benefit Trusts: Roadchef","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the implications of paragraph 181 of the judgement in the case of Roadchef Employees Benefit Trust Ltd v Ingram Hill 2014 for (a) HM Revenue and Customs and (b) the regulation of employees benefit trusts; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","71098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722069","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Government is keen to see all tenants receiving a good service from their landlord and letting agent and the ban on letting fees paid by tenants will give renters greater clarity and control over what they will pay. The consultation on how best to implement the ban has been launched and will be open until 2 June 2017 and includes a question on the potential impacts of the ban.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-25T10:34:18.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722069/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722069/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722069/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-18","Letting Agents: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to ensure that banning upfront fees will not change private sector rent levels.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","71011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722070","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-26","<p>FOI requests may be responded to by any member of staff across the Department, as they are allocated to the most appropriate person to respond depending on the subject of the request.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-04-26T10:49:27.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722070/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722070/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722070/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-18","Department for Communities and Local Government: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many staff in his Department respond to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","71037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722071","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-24","<p>How benefit is paid to claimants is an important consideration in encouraging people to manage their own budget, particularly where it may help claimants moving in to work. That is why Housing Benefit payments in the private rented sector are usually made to the claimant rather than the Landlord. There are existing safeguards in place to help those people who cannot handle their own rent and benefit, including direct payment to Landlords in certain circumstances. There are no plans to change the operation of the Housing Benefit scheme.</p><p> </p><p>The government wants to support good Landlords who provide well maintained homes and avoid further regulation on them which increases costs and red tape, pushes up rents and reduces choice. A range of measures were introduced through the Housing and Planning Act 2016 to crack down on rogue Landlords and we plan to implement these measures in 2017.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-04-24T15:14:14.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722071/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722071/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722071/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-04-18","Housing Benefit: Private Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will bring forward proposals to ensure that housing benefit is paid direct only to landlords, or letting agents, who are Propertymark Protected.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","71104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722072","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-26","<p>We will shortly agree the specifics of each of the 70 projects that successfully applied to the Tampon Tax Fund this year, to ensure that taxpayers' money is put to the best use. We will only make grants where we are 100% certain that they align with the aims of the fund.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","71120 ; 71122 ; 71123 ; 71170 ; 71186","2017-04-26T09:30:49.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722072/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722072/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722072/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-04-18","LIFE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether the funding recently allocated from the Tampon Tax Fund to the Life charity will exclusively be spent on young homeless women who are pregnant.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","71100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722073","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-26","<p>FOI requests may be responded to by any member of staff across the Department, as they are allocated to the most appropriate person to respond depending on the subject of the request.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-04-26T08:53:11.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722073/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722073/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722073/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-04-18","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many staff in her Department respond to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","71038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722074","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-24","<p>In May 2015 the Cyber Security unit moved to DCMS from the Department for Business and Industrial Strategy (BIS).</p><p> </p><p>The department does not retain details centrally that would allow us to identify employees who worked in cyber security roles so the information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-04-24T12:10:36.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722074/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722074/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722074/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-04-18","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many (a) staff of her Department and (b) consultants have been employed in cyber security roles in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","71077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722075","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-24","<p>BBC Monitoring is funded from the television licence fee, which is set by the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport under Section 365 of the Communications Act (2003). The BBC is operationally and editorially independent of Government and funding for the Monitoring scheme is a matter for the BBC.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-04-24T09:37:49.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722075/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722075/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722075/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-04-18","BBC Monitoring","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what future funding she plans to make available to BBC Monitoring.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","71073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722076","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) maintains a central Freedom of Information (FOI) team comprising eleven posts. In addition to these posts, the MOD has a network of focal points across the Department who are responsible for providing FOI guidance within their business area, although this is not their primary function.</p><p>All staff are responsible for ensuring that the Department as a whole is able to meet its legislative obligations under the FOI Act, and can be involved in preparing responses to requests.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-24T15:56:36.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722076/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722076/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722076/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-18","Ministry of Defence: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many staff in his Department respond to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","71039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722077","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>Details of the annual running costs of these sites in each financial year since 2010-11 are not held in the format requested.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-24T15:23:44.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722077/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722077/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722077/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-18","Military Bases: York","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to his Department's report, A Better Defence Estate, published in November 2016, what the annual running costs of (a) Imphal Barracks, (b) Queen Elizabeth II Barracks and (c) Towthorpe Lines have been in each financial year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","71083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722078","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>The following buildings within Imphal Barracks have listed historical status.</p><ul><li>The Keep - Grade II</li><li>Danesmead House - Grade II</li><li>Ousefield House - Grade II</li></ul><p>There are no listed buildings or scheduled monuments at either Queen Elizabeth Barracks or Towthorpe Lines.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-24T15:29:24.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722078/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722078/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722078/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-18","Military Bases: York","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what buildings within the military sites listed in the Better Defence Estate programme in City of York constituency have a listed historical status.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","71060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722079","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Department remains committed to embodying a collision warning system on Typhoon as a priority. Planning is continuing for a feasibility study. Timelines will be informed by this study.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-04-24T15:56:02.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722079/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722079/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722079/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-18","European Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Answer of 14 March 2016 to Question 30993, what the timeline is for the procurement and installation of a collision warning system for the Typhoon aircraft.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","71086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722080","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>The UK contributed two Royal Navy Merlin Mark 2 helicopters and 65 personnel to the NATO-led Exercise Dynamic Manta 2017.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-04-24T15:27:32.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722080/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722080/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722080/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-18","NATO: Military Exercises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) military assets and (b) personnel from his Department took part in NATO exercise Dynamic Manta from 13 to 25 March 2017.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","71066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722081","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>The number of Service Family Accommodation (SFA) and Single Living Accommodation (SLA) units in the vicinity of each of the Ministry of Defence sites requested is shown below as of April 2017.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Site</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>SFA Homes</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>SLA Bedspaces</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>RAF Lossiemouth</p></td><td><p>661</p></td><td><p>c950</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Kinloss Barracks</p></td><td><p>243</p></td><td><p>c830</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Redford Barracks</p></td><td><p>546</p></td><td><p>c420</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Glencorse Barracks</p></td><td><p>159</p></td><td><p>c420</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Fort George Barracks</p></td><td><p>201</p></td><td><p>c480</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HMNB Clyde</p></td><td><p>595</p></td><td><p>c2,390</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The SFA units in the vicinity of Redford Barracks are also used to support other Edinburgh based Service personnel and are not for the exclusive use of Redford Barracks.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-24T15:54:53.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722081/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722081/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722081/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-18","Armed Forces: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 3 April 2017 to Question 69280, how many of the (a) service family accommodation and (b) single living accommodation units are located in, or in the vicinity of, (i) RAF Lossiemouth, (ii) Kinloss Barracks, (iii) Redford Barracks, (iv) Glencorse Barracks, (v) Fort George Barracks and (vi) HMNB Clyde.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","71087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722082","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-20","<p>The information is not held in the format requested.</p><p>Detail of overall expenditure for each equipment type was provided in the answer I gave on 23 March 2017 to Question 68072 to the hon. Member for North Durham (Mr Kevan Jones).</p><p>Ministry of Defence regional expenditure with UK industry was published on 16 March 2017 and can be found at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/mod-regional-expenditure-with-uk-industry-and-supported-employment-201516</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-04-20T15:06:34.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722082/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722082/answer","Hansard Extract 23  March 2017, 68072.docx","Hansard Extract 23  March 2017, 68072.docx","Ministry of Defence- Defence: Expenditure","Ministry of Defence- Defence: Expenditure","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722082/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-18","Ministry of Defence: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 3 April 2017 to Question 69279, what his Department's spend was for (a) submarines, (b) combat air, (c) air support, (d) ships, (e) helicopters, (f) land equipment, (g) weapons and (h) intelligence, surveillance, target acquisition and reconnaissance in (i) England, (ii) Scotland, (iii) Wales and (iv) Northern Ireland since 2013.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","71088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722083","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-25","<p>The F35 reprogramming laboratory that the UK shares with Australia and Canada is located at Eglin Air Force Base in the USA. We cannot specify the exact number of UK personnel for security reasons, however we will ensure the number of personnel deployed is appropriate for the operational task.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-04-25T11:40:57.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722083/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722083/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722083/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-18","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 21 March 2017 to Question 68699, what the location is of the F35 joint programming laboratory the UK shares with Australia; and how many personnel are employed at that facility.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","71089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722084","Department for Education","false","2017-04-27","<p>The Department does not collect data on school attendance orders.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-04-27T11:35:17.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722084/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722084/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722084/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-18","Pupils: Attendance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many school attendance orders have been issued in England since 2000.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","71067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722085","Department for Education","false","2017-04-26","<p>All officials within the Department, as part of their day-to-day work, may respond to requests made under the Freedom of Information Act 2000 within their own areas of responsibility. These are subject to clearance by senior officials.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-04-26T16:29:28.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722085/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722085/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722085/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-18","Department for Education: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many staff in her Department respond to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","71040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722086","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>The data for the last 3 years allocations are in the public domain and can be sourced at the following location:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/16-to-19-education-funding-allocations#published-allocations" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/16-to-19-education-funding-allocations#published-allocations</a></p><p>16-19 funding operates under a lagged funding methodology which uses historic funding factors and student numbers to calculate a funding allocation for each of our c.3,300 funded institutions for each academic year.</p><p>With the exception of c.150 commercial and charitable providers we do not reconcile institutions’ allocated funding to their actual expenditure or funding earned, so we do not operate post 16 funding on the basis of planned and actual expenditure.</p><p>The figures quoted above represent the actual allocations made to institutions for the stated academic years, based on the lagged principle explained above.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-04-24T16:25:12.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722086/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722086/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722086/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-18","Secondary Education: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the (a) planned and (b) actual expenditure on 16-19 education was in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","71090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722087","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector is responsible for Ofsted’s common inspection framework, school inspection handbook and safeguarding guidance, which set out how inspectors consider and report on these matters. The school inspection handbook sets out that inspectors should evaluate the experience of particular individuals and groups, including those with mental health needs.</p><p> </p><p>It also includes as a grade descriptor for outstanding schools that “pupils make informed choices about healthy eating, fitness and their emotional and mental wellbeing”. Inspectors must evaluate how well schools fulfil their statutory and other responsibilities, and how well staff exercise their professional judgement, in keeping pupils safe.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-24T13:55:15.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722087/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722087/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722087/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-18","Secondary Education: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what guidance her Department gives Ofsted inspectors in respect of mental health services offered at secondary schools.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","71071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722088","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 9 January 2017 to Question 58217: <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-12-19/58217/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-12-19/58217/</a>.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-04-24T14:15:10.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722088/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722088/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722088/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-18","Children's Centres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when the Government plans to publish its consultation on the future of children's centres.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","71018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722089","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>Keeping children safe in education is statutory safeguarding guidance for schools and colleges. The guidance sets out that all schools and colleges should have a child protection policy. The child protection policy should reflect the school or college’s approach to sexting.</p><p>To support schools and colleges the UK Council for Child Internet Safety Education Group has recently published advice for schools and colleges. The advice supports them in tackling the range of issues which sexting presents, including responding to disclosures, handling devices and imagery, risk assessing situations and involving other agencies. The advice also contains information about preventative education, working with parents and reporting imagery to providers.</p><p>High quality personal, social, health and economic education and Sex and Relationships Education are a vital part of preparing young people for life in modern Britain - helping young people make informed decisions, manage risks, stay safe and learn to respect themselves and others. Schools have the autonomy to tailor their programmes to reflect the needs of their pupils, and they are free to include teaching to support pupils to manage issues such as sexting.</p><p>The Government has produced advice for schools on searching, screening and confiscation which makes clear that school staff can search pupils for items that have been or could be used to cause harm or break the law, teachers can also search for items banned by the school rules such as mobile phones.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-04-24T14:42:15.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722089/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722089/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722089/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-18","Children: Sexting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to prevent sexting by schoolchildren and to monitor trends in the level of that activity.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","71020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722090","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Deer Act 1991 prohibits, among other things, the poaching of deer as well as the killing or capture of deer during the close season or at night and the use of certain methods of killing or capture. The police are the law enforcement authority for poaching offences.</p><p> </p><p>Poaching is one of the UK’s six wildlife crime priorities. The National Wildlife Crime Unit (NWCU), funded by the Government, is helping the police to tackle these crimes by gathering and analysing information, sharing this with the police and assisting police investigations.</p><p> </p><p>Between 2014 and 2016 the NWCU worked closely with local police and other organisations specifically targeting deer poaching on Exmoor. The action resulted in five arrests and successfully disrupted poaching activity in the area.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-04-24T10:50:14.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722090/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722090/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722090/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-18","Deer: Exmoor National Park","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to protect red deer on Exmoor from the activities of poachers.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","71019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722091","Department of Health","false","2017-04-24","<p>Departments are currently working to understand the impacts that withdrawal from the European Union will have across a number of areas, including understanding any cost implications for the regulatory framework. Options for the future post-exit regulatory framework are being developed that will not compromise the consumer protection or increase burdens on businesses.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-24T10:57:17.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722091/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722091/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722091/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","Food: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the cost of establishing a new regulatory framework for food safety after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Calum Kerr","Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk","Calum Kerr","71015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722092","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-24","<p>We were pleased to hear of China’s announcement to end its domestic commercial ivory trade in 2017. We look forward to seeing further detail on China’s measures, including understanding the nature of provisions for auctioning certified ivory ‘relics’ and how China plans to implement and enforce the new measures.</p><p> </p><p>In September last year, the Environment Secretary announced a ban on trade in worked ivory from the last 70 years, making the UK rules on ivory amongst the toughest in the world. We will consult on these plans.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-04-24T12:01:12.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722092/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722092/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722092/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-18","Ivory: China","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment her Department has made of the implications for its policies of China's recent decision to close its domestic ivory trade.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","71025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722093","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Department of Health (DH) is currently conducting a consultation on the availability of gluten-free foods on NHS prescription, and this is expected to close on 22 June 2017.</p><p> </p><p>It is not the role of Government to set food prices or comment on decisions taken by individual companies. We monitor food prices closely using CPI data, but do not monitor the prices of individual product lines. We work to promote transparency and open global markets internationally, as well as a competitive domestic market to help producers and retailers offer the best prices to consumers. Defra ministers and officials regularly meet representatives of the food retailers.</p><p> </p><p>Officials from Defra and Department of Health (DH) meet regularly to discuss a range of issues relating to health and nutrition policy.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","70703 ; 70704","2017-04-25T10:17:46.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722093/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722093/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722093/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-18","Food: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will hold discussions with supermarkets on the cost of gluten-free foods.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","70997"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722094","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Greenhouse Gas Action Plan (GHGAP) for Agriculture is an industry-led undertaking and the principal mechanism for delivering reductions in emissions from agriculture in England. The recently published review looked at the progress of the GHGAP during the period 2012 through to end of 2016 and recommended changes to further improve performance.</p><p> </p><p>Advice from a number of sources, including the Committee on Climate Change will help us to make reducing greenhouse gas emissions a central part of the Government’s future farming and land use policy and ensure that agriculture contributes to the UK’s legally binding carbon reduction targets.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-04-24T11:30:47.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722094/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722094/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722094/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-18","Agriculture: Greenhouse Gas Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, for what reasons her Department's Greenhouse Gas Action Plan for Agriculture: Review 2016, published on 14 March 2017, did not adopt the Committee on Climate Change October 2016 advice on the need for the Government's approach to agricultural emissions to move beyond the current voluntary approach of providing information and advice; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","71068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722095","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-24","<p>There is no process that provides for the UK to make such applications to the European Commission.</p><p> </p><p>There is a process for “emergency authorisation” of pesticides. Applications for emergency authorisation are made to the UK Government by applicants and are carefully considered on the basis of the scientific evidence and the legal requirements.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-24T12:20:09.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722095/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722095/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722095/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-18","Neonicotinoids: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many applications for the use of neonicotinoid pesticides her Department plans to make to the European Commission during the next 42 months; and how many such applications have been made from the UK in the last (a) 12 and (b) 24 months.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","71069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722096","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-26","<p>FOI requests may be responded to by any member of staff across the Department, as they are allocated to the most appropriate person to respond depending on the subject of the request.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-26T11:56:37.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722096/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722096/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722096/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-18","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many staff in her Department respond to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","71041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722097","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-24","<p>The revised agricultural greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions inventory model is due to be completed this year and implemented as part of the 2016 National Atmospheric Emissions Inventory. Data from the 2016 inventory is due for submission and publication in 2018. Details of the methodology and assumptions within the revised agricultural GHG emissions model will be published in 2018 as part of the annual UK National Inventory Report.</p><p> </p><p>The model will include emissions estimates from:</p><ol><li><p>UK grass and fodder production. Emissions from imported feeds are not accounted for, in line with international emissions reporting guidelines.</p></li><li><p>Carbon sequestration from land converted to grassland. Emissions are accounted for in the Land Use and Land Use Change and Forestry sector.</p><p> </p></li></ol>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-24T14:59:42.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722097/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722097/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722097/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-18","Agriculture: Greenhouse Gas Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when her Department plans to publish the revised greenhouse gas inventory model; whether the updated representation of the UK livestock sector will include data relating to (a) emissions resulting from the production of livestock feed and (b) carbon sequestration in permanent pastures; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","71084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722098","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-24","<p>All wild birds, including ravens, are protected under the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981. Under this Act it is an offence to kill, injure or take wild birds and to take or damage their eggs and nests. There are, however, provisions in section 16 of the Act that allow for the control of birds for the purpose of conserving flora and fauna, for which a licence could be granted. Natural England is the licensing authority in England.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-04-24T14:40:59.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722098/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722098/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722098/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-18","Ravens","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what regulations cover the controlling by shooting or otherwise of ravens which predate on other species; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","71130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722099","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-24","<p>Habitat improvement is a devolved matter. In England, agri-environment schemes such as Environmental Stewardship fund the provision of important habitats for farmland birds such as the grey partridge. In addition, grey partridges are among the farmland birds that will benefit from wild pollinator and farm wildlife package options under the Countryside Stewardship scheme, for example by providing winter feeding, nesting sites and food for chicks.</p><p> </p><p>The grey partridge also benefits - as do other bird species - from England’s extensive network of protected sites for wildlife such as sites of special scientific interest and special protection areas.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-04-24T14:36:01.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722099/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722099/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722099/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-18","Partridges: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to secure habitats for the grey partridge.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","71129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722100","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","Freedom of Information (FOI) requests are dealt with by the relevant teams across the Foreign and Commonwealth Office as a core business function, with support from a small policy advisory team. Accordingly, all staff have a responsibility to respond to FOI requests, as appropriate.","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-04-26T15:37:31.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722100/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722100/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722100/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-18","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many staff in his Department respond to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","71043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722101","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-25","I refer the Hon. Member to my response to written question 70842.","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-04-25T15:25:55.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722101/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722101/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722101/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-18","Chechnya: LGBT People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he is making to the Government of Chechnya on the treatment of LGBT people in that region.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","71059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722102","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to my statement and questions in the House on <a href="https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2017-04-20/debates/B8F6B925-EAA6-4C50-8AB8-31A246B95405/PersecutionAndDetentionOfLGBTCitizensChechnya" target="_blank">Thursday 20 April</a>.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-04-24T16:16:19.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722102/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722102/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722102/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-18","Chechnya: Homosexuality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what information his Department holds on reports of detentions and executions of gay men in Chechnya; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","71093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722103","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>I regularly raise the importance of ensuring humanitarian and commercial access through Hodeidah port with regional partners and the UN.</p><p>Additionally, the Department for International Development is providing £1.4 million for the UN Verification and Inspection Mechanism to speed up the clearance process for ships and improve commercial confidence, as well as £1.8 million to the UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs, who broker humanitarian access for the international response.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-04-24T16:46:00.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722103/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722103/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722103/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-18","Yemen: Ports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to help to ensure that Hudayah port in Yemen remains open to import food and humanitarian aid.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","71094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722104","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>In our regular dialogue with the Israeli government, we discuss a range of security issues, including the strategic threat picture in the region.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-04-24T16:42:41.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722104/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722104/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722104/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-18","Golan Heights: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the Israeli Government on the threat posed by Hezbollah and others on the Golan Heights.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","71023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722105","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Foreign Secretary, has held numerous discussions with the Government of Jordan on retaining and maintaining peace in the Middle East. The Foreign Secretary welcomed His Majesty King Abdullah to London on 26 January during which a wide range of issues were discussed, including the Middle East Peace Process, the Syria conflict, and reconciliation in Iraq. He has also discussed the Syria conflict and countering Daesh with Foreign Minister Al-Safadi in Bonn on 17 February and in Washington on 22 March. In addition to the Foreign Secretary's engagement, the Prime Minister has discussed regional issues with King Abdullah in London on 1 March, and in Jordan on 3 April, where she also met Jordanian PM Al-Mulki.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-04-24T16:40:47.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722105/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722105/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722105/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-18","Jordan: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the Government of Jordan on retaining and maintaining peace in the Middle East.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","71021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722106","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>We have not had any discussions with the US authorities on this issue. We, however, regularly raise the issue of payments to prisoners and their families with senior Palestinian officials. We push them to ensure that such payments are transparent and needs-based.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-04-24T15:34:00.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722106/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722106/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722106/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-18","USA: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his US counterpart on the proposed Taylor Force Act and ending that country's provision of economic aid to the (a) Palestinian Authority and (b) families of those who have died while carrying out terrorist attacks against Israel.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","70994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722107","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Department has not received any representations on the introduction of a standard for chewed tobacco products. The Tobacco and Related Products Regulations 2016 introduced strict marketing rules for all tobacco products, including chewed tobacco products.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-04-26T09:33:04.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722107/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722107/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722107/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","Tobacco: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what representations he has received on introducing a standard for chewed tobacco products; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","70996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722108","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>From April 2017, the functions of NHS Protect have changed. Work is underway to create a new special health authority, called the NHS Counter Fraud Authority. The focus of the new organisation will be exclusively on tackling fraud, bribery and corruption across the National Health Service and the wider health group. The new authority will not have a remit for security management work.</p><p> </p><p>Employers in the NHS are responsible for assessing risks to staff and addressing those risks. Any abuse of NHS staff is unacceptable and should not be tolerated. Any form of abuse should be reported and trusts should have no hesitation in involving the police. Comprehensive and detailed guidance is available to NHS employers to assist them in assessing and managing the risks accordingly and involving the police where appropriate. A separate NHS national alert system is therefore unnecessary.</p><p> </p><p>The standards for security management work are imposed through the relevant clauses of the standard commissioning contract between commissioners and providers. It is commissioners’ responsibility to ensure that security management standards are met in accordance with the contract. NHS England is responsible for the standard commissioning contract and the clauses within it.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","71101","2017-04-26T14:27:50.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722108/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722108/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722108/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","NHS: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will commission a national alert system on security-related issues and individuals who may post a significant present or potential threat to NHS staff, NHS service providers and NHS property assets.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","70999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722109","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Department is working on ensuring the best outcome for the health and social care system. All policy teams within the Department are involved with this work and assessing the implications of the United Kingdom leaving the European Union on their area. This includes working with NHS England and other arm’s length bodies.</p><p> </p><p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Prime Minister has instructed all departments to identify potential opportunities that will arise in their areas from EU Exit. The Government is united in its ambition to deliver a successful withdrawal from the EU and a new relationship with Europe, and departments will work together to deliver this.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-26T10:30:54.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722109/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722109/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722109/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","NHS","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make it his policy to conduct an analysis of the potential effects of the UK leaving the EU on the NHS.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","71013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722110","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>A final decision has yet to be taken on the sensitivity threshold for the faecal immunochemical test on its introduction to the bowel cancer screening programme in April 2018. Setting the threshold will require the balancing of a number of different factors, including how endoscopy capacity is affected.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","71211","2017-04-26T10:16:05.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722110/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722110/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722110/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","Bowel Cancer: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what sensitivity threshold the faecal immunochemical test will be set when it is introduced into the bowel cancer screening programme.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","71005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722111","Department of Health","false","2017-04-24","<p>The new Apprenticeship Levy came into operation in April 2017 for employers with a with a pay bill over £3 million each year and is set at 0.5% of pay bill. All National Health Service trusts will come within scope for paying the apprentice levy, with an estimated total NHS levy contribution of up to £200 million in 2017/18.</p><p>Doncaster and Bassetlaw will come within scope to pay the apprentice levy.</p><p>NHS trusts can employ apprentices in a range of clinical and non-clinical roles in the next two years including nursing, healthcare science, dental nursing, healthcare support worker, ambulance practitioner accountancy, business administration, digital and technology roles.</p><p>New apprenticeship roles are in development across a range of regulated healthcare professions including, the new Nursing Associate role, Occupational Therapy, Physiotherapy, Paramedic and Social Worker.</p><p>The new Public Sector Apprentice Target applies to public sector bodies with 250 or more staff in England and requires a minimum of 2.3% new apprentice starts each year based on the headcount of employees. The total NHS apprentice target is estimated as 27,500 in 2017/18.</p><p>Latest information from NHS Digital indicates that Doncaster and Bassetlaw Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust directly employs 6,497 headcount people. The Department estimates Doncaster and Bassetlaw Hospitals would need to employ 149 apprentices in 2017/18 to meet the Public Sector Apprentice Target.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","71148","2017-04-24T15:30:25.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722111/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722111/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722111/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","NHS Trusts: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many NHS Trusts are required to pay the apprenticeship levy; how much in total NHS Trusts will pay; in which areas of employment NHS Trusts will create apprenticeships in the next two years; and how many apprenticeships NHS Trusts will create.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","71082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722112","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>Working with partner organisations on the National Cancer Transformation Board, including the Department, Health Education England will publish a cancer workforce plan later this year which will set out the future cancer workforce requirements for the National Health Service and what can be done to achieve them.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-26T10:17:24.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722112/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722112/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722112/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with Health Education England on the level of its baseline cancer workforce; and whether that body has developed a system-wide action plan to address capacity issues.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","71055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722113","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Department does not have this information. Each Freedom of Information request could typically involve a variety of staff from our Call Centre, Ministerial Correspondence and Public Enquiries team, the relevant policy team and a senior civil servant.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-26T10:23:40.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722113/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722113/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722113/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","Department of Health: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many staff in his Department respond to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","71044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722114","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>We have made no recent assessment of the effectiveness of the Strategic Projects team, which was disbanded in July 2016.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-26T10:11:32.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722114/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722114/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722114/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","NHS","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the NHS Special Projects team.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","71142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722115","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>Smoking attributable deaths from heart disease have fallen by over 26% since 2007, but smoking remains one of the Government’s most significant public health challenges. We are developing a new tobacco control plan that will set new ambitions and focus on supporting priority groups to quit.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-04-26T09:35:25.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722115/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722115/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722115/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","Heart Diseases: Smoking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the risk of heart disease to women who smoke.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","71131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722116","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>The responsibility for the decision to commission with BMI Fawkham Manor rests with the clinical commissioning group (CCG). This is its statutory role, while assuring the safety and quality of the providers they choose to commission with.</p><p> </p><p>We understand that the Dartford, Swanley and Gravesham CCG is working with regulators and other partners to monitor and assess BMI Fawkham Manor Hospital’s progress towards improvement. Since the inspection, BMI has set out a detailed action plan to address the Care Quality Commission’s findings.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-04-26T14:29:16.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722116/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722116/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722116/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","BMI Healthcare: Kent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he has made an assessment of NHS patient safety at the BMI Healthcare hospital in Kent as a result of the recent inadequate assessment by the Care Quality Commission; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","71143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722117","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Government continues to support research through a range of funding agencies into the therapeutic use of stem cells. Over 80 patients have been recruited to a clinical trial to test the potential use of stem cells to treat liver disease. The results of this trial will only be available when the follow-up phase of the study has been completed. Before making this type of treatment available through the National Health Service it will be necessary to demonstrate that the treatment is both safe and effective and this is likely to involve further larger clinical trials.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-04-26T09:22:39.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722117/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722117/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722117/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","Liver Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to encourage innovative stem cell and umbilical cord treatments for liver disease.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","71132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722118","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>In current NHS England commissioning practice, testing for Lynch syndrome in people with colorectal cancer is targeted using criteria based on family history and age of cancer onset to determine people at high risk.</p><p> </p><p>New National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) guidance recommends extending this offer to all people with colorectal cancer when they are first diagnosed. Offering tests to all people with colorectal cancer will need to be considered by NHS England as part of its policy development process. Each year, a number of new drugs, medical devices, tests and treatments in specialised services are put forward to NHS England. The promising proposals are considered by experts in the field, including doctors, public health experts and lay people. These groups, established by NHS England, are known as Clinical Reference Groups (CRGs). The CRGs make detailed assessments of the new treatments, tests and devices through Policy Working Groups.</p><p> </p><p>The NICE guidance has been sent to the Genetic Medicine CRG and they have been asked to submit a Preliminary Policy Proposal and to identify a Clinical Lead for progressing the proposal.</p><p> </p><p>Consideration of the commissioning position and any financial implications will only be discussed once the proposal has been rigorously assessed.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","71184","2017-04-26T10:27:15.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722118/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722118/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722118/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","Bowel Cancer: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what additional funding will be made available to ensure that hospitals and clinical commissioning groups have the resources required to implement new NICE guidance recommending that all patients newly diagnosed with bowel cancer are tested for Lynch syndrome.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","71103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722119","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Government has committed to an extra 5,000 doctors in general practice by 2020.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England and Health Education England are working together with the profession to increase the general practitioner (GP) workforce. This includes measures to boost recruitment into general practice, encourage GPs to return to practice, and address the reasons why GPs are considering leaving the profession.</p><p> </p><p>Health Education England has implemented a range of improvements to increase the flexibility of the GP recruitment processes and enable maximum recruitment into GP speciality. Health Education England reports that 3,019 new starters were recruited to GP training posts in 2016. This represents the highest number of GP trainees the National Health Service has ever recruited to speciality training in general practice.</p><p> </p><p>In October 2016, NHS England announced a package of improvements to the GP Induction and Refresher Scheme to make it easier and quicker for qualified doctors to return to general practice. This is supplemented by a campaign to encourage doctors to return. NHS England is also starting to approve local schemes to bring in suitably qualified and experienced doctors from overseas.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has announced the launch of the GP Career Plus Scheme in 2017 to support the retention of doctors. This tests a range of ways to offer flexibility and support for experienced GPs at risk of leaving general practice. This is in addition to the GP Retention Scheme which offers funding to support doctors who can only work a limited number of sessions in general practice.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-26T10:20:23.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722119/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722119/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722119/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","General Practitioners: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent steps his Department has taken to improve recruitment and retention of GPs.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","71133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722120","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>The standards for security management work are imposed through the relevant clauses of the standard commissioning contract between commissioners and providers. It is the responsibility for commissioners to ensure that security management standards are met in accordance with the contract. NHS England is responsible for the standard commissioning contract, the clauses within it and the standards to which it refers.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Protect has never had responsibility for counter terrorism work in the National Health Service. This rests with the Emergency Preparedness, Resilience and Response branch within NHS England.</p><p> </p><p>The figures previously published by NHS Protect were a collation of the numbers of reported assaults provided by individual health bodies. Employers in the NHS are responsible for assessing the circumstances of these reported assaults and addressing the risks identified and this work will continue at a local level where it is best delivered.</p><p> </p><p>The role of NHS Protect was to develop national guidance to assist NHS organisations locally in their security management work. Comprehensive and detailed guidance is now available to NHS employers who are responsible for assessing risks to staff and addressing those risks. It was not, therefore, necessary for a separate risk assessment to be undertaken as this change should have no effect on the safety of NHS staff.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","71106 ; 71145 ; 71146 ; 71147","2017-04-26T14:25:13.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722120/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722120/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722120/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","NHS Protect","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, who will assume responsibility for the counter-terrorism security preparedness functions undertaken by NHS Protect following its change of role.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","71144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722121","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>The standards for security management work are imposed through the relevant clauses of the standard commissioning contract between commissioners and providers. It is the responsibility for commissioners to ensure that security management standards are met in accordance with the contract. NHS England is responsible for the standard commissioning contract, the clauses within it and the standards to which it refers.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Protect has never had responsibility for counter terrorism work in the National Health Service. This rests with the Emergency Preparedness, Resilience and Response branch within NHS England.</p><p> </p><p>The figures previously published by NHS Protect were a collation of the numbers of reported assaults provided by individual health bodies. Employers in the NHS are responsible for assessing the circumstances of these reported assaults and addressing the risks identified and this work will continue at a local level where it is best delivered.</p><p> </p><p>The role of NHS Protect was to develop national guidance to assist NHS organisations locally in their security management work. Comprehensive and detailed guidance is now available to NHS employers who are responsible for assessing risks to staff and addressing those risks. It was not, therefore, necessary for a separate risk assessment to be undertaken as this change should have no effect on the safety of NHS staff.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","71106 ; 71144 ; 71146 ; 71147","2017-04-26T14:25:13.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722121/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722121/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722121/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","NHS Protect","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whose role it is to keep central records of assaults on NHS staff following the change of role of NHS Protect.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","71145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722122","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>The UK National Screening Committee (UK NSC) recommends screening for several conditions in pregnancy. The case for continuation or otherwise of these programmes is reviewed as per the UK NSC’s evidence review process, every three years or earlier should any significant new evidence emerge.</p><p> </p><p>In November 2014, the UK NSC recommended that screening for pre-term birth should not be offered as the available screening test is not reliable. The UK NSC will review the evidence for preterm labour again in 2017/18.</p><p> </p><p>Women are offered a minimum of two ultrasound scans during their pregnancy to screen for physical (structural) abnormalities in their unborn babies. The first scan usually takes place between 10 to 14 weeks, with a second scan for fetal anomalies at around 18 to 21 weeks. This scan can detect a large range of problems including some affecting the heart and abdomen. Early treatment after birth for these can help save a baby’s life.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-04-26T14:22:18.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722122/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722122/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722122/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","Pregnancy: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what developments the NHS plans for tests to detect possible premature birth; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","71134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722123","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>The standards for security management work are imposed through the relevant clauses of the standard commissioning contract between commissioners and providers. It is the responsibility for commissioners to ensure that security management standards are met in accordance with the contract. NHS England is responsible for the standard commissioning contract, the clauses within it and the standards to which it refers.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Protect has never had responsibility for counter terrorism work in the National Health Service. This rests with the Emergency Preparedness, Resilience and Response branch within NHS England.</p><p> </p><p>The figures previously published by NHS Protect were a collation of the numbers of reported assaults provided by individual health bodies. Employers in the NHS are responsible for assessing the circumstances of these reported assaults and addressing the risks identified and this work will continue at a local level where it is best delivered.</p><p> </p><p>The role of NHS Protect was to develop national guidance to assist NHS organisations locally in their security management work. Comprehensive and detailed guidance is now available to NHS employers who are responsible for assessing risks to staff and addressing those risks. It was not, therefore, necessary for a separate risk assessment to be undertaken as this change should have no effect on the safety of NHS staff.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","71106 ; 71144 ; 71145 ; 71147","2017-04-26T14:25:13.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722123/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722123/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722123/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","NHS Protect","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will publish the risk assessment undertaken by his Department before the decision was taken to change the remit of NHS Protect.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","71146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722124","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>The standards for security management work are imposed through the relevant clauses of the standard commissioning contract between commissioners and providers. It is the responsibility for commissioners to ensure that security management standards are met in accordance with the contract. NHS England is responsible for the standard commissioning contract, the clauses within it and the standards to which it refers.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Protect has never had responsibility for counter terrorism work in the National Health Service. This rests with the Emergency Preparedness, Resilience and Response branch within NHS England.</p><p> </p><p>The figures previously published by NHS Protect were a collation of the numbers of reported assaults provided by individual health bodies. Employers in the NHS are responsible for assessing the circumstances of these reported assaults and addressing the risks identified and this work will continue at a local level where it is best delivered.</p><p> </p><p>The role of NHS Protect was to develop national guidance to assist NHS organisations locally in their security management work. Comprehensive and detailed guidance is now available to NHS employers who are responsible for assessing risks to staff and addressing those risks. It was not, therefore, necessary for a separate risk assessment to be undertaken as this change should have no effect on the safety of NHS staff.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","71106 ; 71144 ; 71145 ; 71146","2017-04-26T14:25:13.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722124/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722124/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722124/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","NHS Protect","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the change of role of NHS Protect on the safety of staff; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","71147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722125","Department of Health","false","2017-04-25","<p>The total amount that clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) were asked to set aside at the start of the 2016-17 financial year was 1% of non-recurrent expenditure totalling £707 million, plus a further £92 million within NHS England direct commissioning. Neither in the case of CCGs nor NHS England direct commissioners was the money held back.</p><p> </p><p>It would be for each individual CCG to plan spending the 1% non-recurrent monies – therefore this information would not be held, though NHS England would expect and encourage the CCGs to invest the money in transformation.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","70419 ; 71065","2017-04-25T12:45:48.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722125/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722125/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722125/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","Clinical Commissioning Groups: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the plans were for spending the contingency fund held back from clinical commissioning groups in 2016-17 in the event that it had not been used to offset financial deficits among NHS Trusts.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","71064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722126","Department of Health","false","2017-04-25","<p>The total amount that clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) were asked to set aside at the start of the 2016-17 financial year was 1% of non-recurrent expenditure totalling £707 million, plus a further £92 million within NHS England direct commissioning. Neither in the case of CCGs nor NHS England direct commissioners was the money held back.</p><p> </p><p>It would be for each individual CCG to plan spending the 1% non-recurrent monies – therefore this information would not be held, though NHS England would expect and encourage the CCGs to invest the money in transformation.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","70419 ; 71064","2017-04-25T12:45:48.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722126/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722126/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722126/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","Clinical Commissioning Groups: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what amount of the contingency fund held back from clinical commissioning groups in 2016-17 on account of that fund being used to offset financial deficits had been earmarked for Lambeth and Southwark clinical commissioning groups.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","71065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722127","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>From April 2017, the functions of NHS Protect have changed. Work is underway to create a new special health authority, called the NHS Counter Fraud Authority. The focus of the new organisation will be exclusively on tackling fraud, bribery and corruption across the National Health Service and the wider health group. The new authority will not have a remit for security management work.</p><p> </p><p>Employers in the NHS are responsible for assessing risks to staff and addressing those risks. Any abuse of NHS staff is unacceptable and should not be tolerated. Any form of abuse should be reported and trusts should have no hesitation in involving the police. Comprehensive and detailed guidance is available to NHS employers to assist them in assessing and managing the risks accordingly and involving the police where appropriate. A separate NHS national alert system is therefore unnecessary.</p><p> </p><p>The standards for security management work are imposed through the relevant clauses of the standard commissioning contract between commissioners and providers. It is commissioners’ responsibility to ensure that security management standards are met in accordance with the contract. NHS England is responsible for the standard commissioning contract and the clauses within it.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","70999","2017-04-26T14:27:50.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722127/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722127/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722127/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","NHS Protect","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which organisations will have responsibility for ensuring that NHS providers comply with security standards following the decommissioning of NHS Protect's security management functions.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","71101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722128","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Staffordshire Cancer and End of Life Programme advises that the costs for both the cancer and end of life procurements over a three year period up to October 2016 equates to £848,000. This has been funded by Cannock Chase, Stafford and Surrounds, North Staffordshire and Stoke on Trent Clinical Commissioning Groups. The cost to each clinical commissioning group over the three years is circa £200,000 which is £65,000 per annum. The four clinical commissioning groups’ total commissioning budget is circa £800 million per annum.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-26T10:29:18.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722128/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722128/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722128/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","Cancer: Staffordshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the cost to the public purse was of the cancelled tender for cancer services in Staffordshire.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","71141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722129","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Health regularly meets with clinical bodies to discuss a wide range of issues including the diagnosis and treatment of people with motor neurone disease.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-26T10:24:53.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722129/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722129/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722129/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","Motor Neurone Disease: Electromagnetic Fields","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with clinical bodies on the potential link between motor neurone disease and exposure to strong electro-magnetic charges in the (a) electricity network, (b) airline, (c) welding and (d) other industries.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","71135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722130","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Department does not hold data on the number of patients diagnosed with amyloidosis.</p><p> </p><p>The National Amyloidosis Centre at University College Hospital, London estimates that there are around 600 new cases of the condition each year.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-04-26T09:25:38.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722130/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722130/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722130/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","Amyloidosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people have been diagnosed with amyloidosis in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","71136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722131","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>In the United Kingdom the provision of in vitro fertilisation (IVF) is regulated by the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Act 1990, as amended (1990 Act). Establishments wishing to provide IVF treatment must first be granted a licence from the UK national regulator, the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority (HFEA). The 1990 Act requires that all IVF treatment cycles are reported to the HFEA. As part of the Authority’s duty to ensure that safe, high quality care is provided to patients, it is required by the 1990 Act to inspect all licensed establishments a minimum of once every two years.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has no role in the regulation of IVF provision and does not collect statistics about this. NHS England is responsible for oversight of the commissioning system. I wrote to NHS England on 7 March 2017 asking that it re-emphasise to all those involved in commissioning fertility services that they should have regard to the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) fertility guideline.</p><p> </p><p>The Department, NHS England and professional and stakeholder groups are working together to develop benchmark pricing for fertility services to ensure that clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) can get best value for their money. These partners are also developing commissioning guidance. This guidance aims to improve the quality of commissioning and encourage the full implementation of the NICE fertility guidance. NHS England has agreed to disseminate and promote the guidance to all CCGs in England.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-04-26T09:37:38.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722131/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722131/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722131/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","In Vitro Fertilisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department takes to (a) regulate and (b) monitor the provision of IVF treatment.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","71137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722132","Home Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>In February 2017, the Government published its <em>Tackling Child Sexual Exploitation: Progress Report</em> which reported that 90% of the actions in the March 2015 <em>Tackling Child Sexual Exploitation Report</em> had been delivered, including investment in the frontline response to child sexual abuse, e.g. recruiting around an extra 100 specialist rape and child sexual abuse prosecutors, establishing new investigative teams in the National Crime Agency, and launching a new Child Sexual Exploitation Response Unit to support social care, health and other agencies.</p><p>In February the Government announced a £40 million package of measures to protect children and young people from sexual abuse, exploitation and trafficking and to crack down on offenders. The package included £7.5 million for a new ground-breaking Centre of Expertise on Child Sexual Abuse, an extra £20 million for the National Crime Agency to tackle online child sexual exploitation, and £2.2 million for organisations working to protect children at risk of trafficking.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-04-24T12:24:10.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722132/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722132/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722132/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-04-18","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent steps her Department has taken to reduce the number of child sexual offences.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","71128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722133","Home Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>Except where someone has fraudulently obtained British citizenship, deprivation of citizenship is only pursued against dual nationals where the Home Secretary is satisfied that the statutory test that deprivation of citizenship would be “conducive to the public good”, is met. To date, deprivation of citizenship on conducive grounds has been focused on protecting the UK from those involved in terrorism, unacceptable extremist behaviour, espionage or serious organised crime.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-04-24T13:38:16.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722133/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722133/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722133/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-04-18","British Nationality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people were deprived of UK citizenship for actions seriously prejudicial to the vital interests of the UK in each of the three years since the Immigration Act 2014 has come into force.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","71102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722134","Home Office","false","2017-04-20","<p>The information is not held centrally and could be obtained only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-04-20T14:47:44.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722134/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722134/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722134/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-04-18","Home Office: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many staff in her Department respond to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","71045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722135","Home Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>We are in ongoing dialogue with the French authorities regarding the incident at the Dunkirk camp. The primary responsibility for unaccompanied children in Europe lies with the State in which they are present. We are committed to making sure that the Dublin III Regulation works effectively to ensure that unaccompanied asylum-seeking children are reunited as soon as possible with any close family members in the UK, as set out in the Regulation.</p><p>Under the Dublin III Regulation, an unaccompanied child must first claim asylum in the EU Member State in which they are present, and that Member State must then raise a take charge request with the UK Government. It is therefore vital that children remaining in France who have close family in the UK engage with the French authorities to make an asylum claim and enable the process to start.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-04-24T13:39:20.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722135/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722135/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722135/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-04-18","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that children who have family in the UK who were affected by the Dunkirk refugee camp fire are reunited with their families as soon as possible.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","71058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722136","Home Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>We are currently developing the new Drug Strategy, working across government and with key partners. The new strategy will be published in due course.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-04-24T12:22:12.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722136/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722136/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722136/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-04-18","Drugs: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when the Government's new Drug Strategy will be published.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","71008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722137","Home Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>In accordance with our international obligations, the UK is required to consider asylum and human rights applications carefully on their individual merits. The Government takes its international responsibilities seriously and will grant protection to those in genuine need.</p><p>Each individual assessment of an asylum claim is made against the background of the latest available country of origin information and any relevant caselaw. The country of origin information is based on evidence taken from a range of reliable sources, including reputable media outlets; local, national and international organisations, including human rights organisations; and information from the Foreign and Commonwealth Office.</p><p>No country specific guidance has been issued on asylum applications made by supporters of Biafran independence. However, where a particular issue is raised in an individual application caseworkers can request the latest available country information on that issue through an information request service.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-04-24T13:44:08.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722137/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722137/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722137/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-04-18","Politics and Government: Nigeria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the safety of returning supporters of Biafran independence to Nigeria.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","71004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722138","Department for International Development","false","2017-04-24","<p>DFID has a central team of three staff who advise on and co-ordinate responses to Freedom of Information requests. All DFID staff may have some involvement in preparing responses.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-04-24T16:55:45.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722138/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722138/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722138/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-04-18","Department for International Development: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many staff in her Department respond to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","71046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722139","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-26","<p>FOI requests may be responded to by any member of staff across the Department, as they are allocated to the most appropriate person to respond depending on the subject of the request. The Ministry of Justice has a central Disclosure Team to support this function.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-04-26T12:46:23.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722139/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722139/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722139/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-04-18","Ministry of Justice: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many staff in her Department respond to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","71048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722140","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-24","<p>A government response to the consultation “Driving Offences and Penalties relating to causing death and serious injury” will be published as soon as possible but will be subject to the normal restrictions that apply during the period before a general election.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-04-24T10:04:33.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722140/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722140/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722140/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-04-18","Dangerous Driving","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when the Government plans to publish its response to its consultation on Driving Offences and Penalties relating to causing Death or Serious Injury, issued in December 2016.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","71099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722141","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Ministry of Justice is committed to helping victims, including family members, cope with, and recover from, crime. The majority of the department’s victims’ services budget now goes to Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs) to deliver support services for victims of crime in their local areas. The rest goes directly to victims charities and other organisations to provide support to victims.</p><p>The department uses a range of measures to monitor performance. Some services (delivered by charities and PCCs) provide information on the number and types of intervention, rather than the number of victims supported and therefore complete information on the number of victims supported cannot be provided. Work is currently underway to develop a consistent set of measures across all services including those delivered by PCCs.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014/15 <sup>1</sup></strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016/17</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>National MoJ grants<sup>2</sup></strong></p></td><td><p>c£47m (including almost £21m to Victim Support for a national referral service)</p></td><td><p>c£21m</p></td><td><p>c£22m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Number of charities receiving grants</strong></p></td><td><p>Over 180</p></td><td><p>Over 110</p></td><td><p>Over 110</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Grants to PCCs</strong></p></td><td><p>c£35m</p></td><td><p>c£61m</p></td><td><p>c£68m</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong><sup>1</sup></strong> 2014/15 was a transitional year for funding with a move from nationally commissioned services to a mixed national-local model with local services delivered by PCCs with MoJ funding.</p><p><strong><sup>2 </sup></strong>Including funding for the court-based Witness Service.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-04-26T17:35:20.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722141/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722141/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722141/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-04-18","Crime: Victims","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what funding her Department provided to victims charities in each of the last three years; and how many victims and their families each charity has supported with that funding.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","71061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722142","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-26","<p>The number and length of custodial sentence for female offenders, in England and Wales, from 2011 to 2015 can be viewed in the table attached.</p><p>Data for 2016 is intended for publication on the Ministry of Justice website on 18 May 2017.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-04-26T17:31:25.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722142/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722142/answer","Final table PQ 71001.xls","Final table PQ 71001.xls","Table for PQ 71001","Table for PQ 71001","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722142/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-04-18","Offenders: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many female offenders received an immediate sentence of (a) fewer than six months and (b) six months or more, by offence group, in each police force area in (i) Wales and (ii) England in 2011 to 2016.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","71001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722143","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-27","<p>Information about the number and outcomes of personal independence payment appeals in Scotland is published on gov.uk. The most recent statistics, for the period October to December 2016, can be viewed at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-2016" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-2016</a>.</p><p> </p><p>HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service cannot isolate cost data relating to specific benefit types.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","71017","2017-04-27T13:27:54.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722143/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722143/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722143/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-04-18","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of appeals to the Tribunals Service in Scotland relating to personal independence payments were successful in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","71016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722144","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-27","<p>Information about the number and outcomes of personal independence payment appeals in Scotland is published on gov.uk. The most recent statistics, for the period October to December 2016, can be viewed at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-2016" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-2016</a>.</p><p> </p><p>HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service cannot isolate cost data relating to specific benefit types.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","71016","2017-04-27T13:27:54.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722144/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722144/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722144/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-04-18","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many appeals to the Tribunals Service in Scotland related to personal independence payments in the latest period for which figures are available; and what the total cost was of those appeals.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","71017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722145","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>FOI requests may be responded to by any member of staff across the Department, as they are allocated to the most appropriate person to respond depending on the subject of the request.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2017-04-26T09:54:53.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722145/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722145/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722145/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-04-18","Northern Ireland Office: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many staff in his Department respond to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","71049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722146","Scotland Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>Depending on the nature of the request and to ensure an appropriate response, staff from across the Department are involved in responding to Freedom of Information requests.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-04-24T09:48:49.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722146/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722146/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722146/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-04-18","Scotland Office: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many staff in his Department respond to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","71050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722147","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-26","<p>Freedom of Information requests are responded to by the most appropriate person in the Department, based on the subject matter of the request. This means that any member of staff may be responsible for answering requests, which are allocated to them on a case-by-case basis.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-04-26T10:45:45.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722147/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722147/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722147/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-18","Department for Transport: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many staff in his Department respond to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","71051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722148","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA) has recently published its five year strategy – ‘Helping you stay safe on Britain’s roads’. At the same time it also published its 2017/18 Business Plan which contains key performance indicators that contribute towards the successful delivery of the first year of its strategy.</p><p> </p><p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) has recently published its Strategic Plan for 2017-20, alongside its Business Plan 2017-18. DVLA’s aim is to get the right drivers and vehicles taxed and on the road, as simply, safely and efficiently as possible.</p><p> </p><p>As Sponsor of DVSA and DVLA my Department approved the content of both their strategies and business plans.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-04-24T13:53:31.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722148/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722148/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722148/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-18","Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency and Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions the Government has had on the key performance indicators for the objectives set out in the newly published business strategies for the (a) Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency and (b) DVLA with those agencies.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","70995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722149","Home Office","false","2017-04-21","<p>This information is not collected centrally. It is a matter for Chief Constables, working with their Police and Crime Commissioners, to determine how to use available resources according to local priorities.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-04-21T14:44:25.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722149/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722149/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722149/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-04-18","Road Traffic Offences: Speed Limits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much police authorities spent on the provision of diversionary courses for speed awareness in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","70998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722150","Wales Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>Any member of staff in the Wales Office might respond to Freedom of Information requests depending on the context of the information being requested.</p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2017-04-24T14:30:21.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722150/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722150/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722150/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-04-18","Wales Office: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many staff in his Department respond to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","71053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722151","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Government wants to see greater diversity on the boards of the FTSE’s largest companies, and wants to see that delivered through a business-led approach. That approach has seen the proportion of women on FTSE100 boards increase from 12.5% in 2010 to nearly 27% as at April 2017. We now want to extend that progress to ethnic, as well as gender, diversity.</p><p>Sir John Parker’s Review is an industry-led review, and its recommendations will be for the private sector to consider. However, the Government will keep a close eye on how things develop, and consider whether it needs to take action once Sir John finalises his recommendations before the end of this year.</p><p>The boardroom must reflect modern Britain. Companies will do better if they make better use of the talent available and ensure their boardrooms reflect their workforces and wider society. Sir John’s Review is an important, industry-led contribution to this debate.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-04-25T09:13:24.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722151/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722151/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722151/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-18","Directors: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that the recommendations of the Parker Review on increasing the ethnic diversity of UK boards are implemented.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","71032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722152","Women and Equalities","false","2017-04-21","<p>We understand that the claimants in this case have sought permission to appeal to the Supreme Court. We are currently awaiting the Court’s decision on whether to allow the appeal so we are unable to comment further on the case.</p><p>As you know, a General Election has been called. This means that a decision on this policy area will be for the next Government.</p><p>As we set out previously, the Government carried out a consultation on the future of civil partnerships in 2014. The review found that there was no clear consensus on the future of civil partnerships. Given the lack of any consensus, the Government did not change the Civil Partnership Act 2004.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-04-21T14:51:16.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722152/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722152/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722152/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-04-18","Civil Partnerships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, pursuant to the Answer of 3 April 2017 to Question 69447, on civil partnerships, whether she plans for an assessment of the effect of the equalisation of civil partnerships between same sex and different sex couples to take place before the Supreme Court has heard and given judgement in the appeal by Steinfeld and Another in their case against the Department for Education.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","71054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722153","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Advisory Committee on the Safety of Blood Tissues and Organs is currently reviewing blood donor selection criteria, including the deferral period for men who have sex with men. The review is on track to be completed by summer 2017.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-04-26T09:21:07.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722153/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722153/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722153/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","Blood: Donors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans the Government has to remove the bar on men who have sex with men seeking to donate blood.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","71026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722154","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-04-27","<p>In the negotiations, the Government will discuss with the EU and Member States how best to continue to cooperate in the field of medicines regulation in the best interests of both the UK and EU. It would not be appropriate to pre-judge the outcome of the negotiations.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-04-27T09:21:27.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722154/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722154/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722154/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-04-18","EU Institutions: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what estimate his Department has made of the number of job losses that will arise when the European Medicines Agency and the European Banking Authority leave the UK.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","71009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722155","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-24","<p>Claimants will not be required to disclose sensitive personal data as part of the (HWC). The paperwork from the HWC is taken away by the claimant at the end of the conversation. DWP staff will update records to show that the HWC has taken place, record any voluntary actions and any support offered by DWP.</p><p> </p><p>The Department treats the protection of sensitive personal data extremely seriously and safeguards such data in compliance with the Data Protection Act and in accordance with Departmental security policies and standards;</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-04-24T11:07:32.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722155/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722155/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722155/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-04-18","Employment and Support Allowance: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans he has to safeguard sensitive personal data potentially discussed in the proposed new health and work conversation for employment and support allowance claimants; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","71091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722156","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-24","<p>There are currently 16 customer access computers in the Glasgow South West constituency, and customers also have the option of using their own personal devices by connecting to the free Wi-Fi in Jobcentres. Customers are able to access Universal Jobmatch or apply for Universal Credit from any computer.</p><p> </p><p>Where customers can access our services independently they are encouraged to do so. However, we also provide an assisted service for customers that require additional support to use the computers.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-04-24T16:04:19.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722156/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722156/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722156/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-04-18","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many public access computer terminals there are for searching Universal Jobmatch and applying for universal credit across the Jobcentre Plus network in the Glasgow South West constituency.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","71097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722157","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>Since answering the question on 16<sup>th</sup> March 2017 BEIS has identified a source for this information.</p><p>The table below shows how much coal the UK cement industry used each year from 2005-2015:</p><p><strong><em>Coal consumption by UK cement industry, 2005-2015 (coal used in tonnes)</em></strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>2005</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2006</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2007</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2008</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2009</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>959,450</p></td><td><p>875,255</p></td><td><p>1,150,252</p></td><td><p>919,016</p></td><td><p>572,618</p></td><td><p>592,447</p></td><td><p>602,976</p></td><td><p>497,901</p></td><td><p>483,807</p></td><td><p>530,371</p></td><td><p>569,253</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>This reduction was in part due to the industry switching to waste-derived alternative fuels, including biomass.</p><p> </p><p><em>Source: Mineral Products Association</em></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-04-24T11:15:00.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722157/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722157/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722157/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-18","Cement: Coal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much coal the UK cement industry used in each year from 2005 to the latest year for which figures are available; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","71062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722158","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy does not hold data on coal consumption at this level of disaggregation.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-04-24T11:15:15.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722158/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722158/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722158/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-18","Plastics: Coal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what quality of steam coal the UK carbon fibre industry requires; where it currently sources coal; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","71063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722159","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy does not have a specific number of staff tasked with responding to Freedom of Information (FOI) requests. On receipt FOI requests are allocated to officials in the area of the Department relevant to the subject of the request who provide the response.</p><p>The Department’s Information Rights Unit (IRU) processes all FOI requests and provides advice and assistance to policy officials on the application of information rights legislation. The IRU consists of eight members of staff.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-04-24T15:35:50.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722159/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722159/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722159/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-18","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many staff in his Department respond to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","71034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722160","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Government is fully committed to maintaining the UK’s world-leading science, research and higher education base.</p><p> </p><p>According to Higher Education Statistics Agency (HESA) data, the University of Chichester in West Sussex received public research funding, from Higher Education Funding Council for England and the Research Councils, of £802,000 in 2015/16. HESA data shows that 19 institutions in the South East, which includes the universities of Oxford, Southampton and Reading, but excludes London, received a total of £544 million of public research funding in 2015/16.</p><p> </p><p>The Autumn Statement 2016 announcement of an extra £2 billion a year in research and development by 2020- 21 underlines the place of science and innovation at the heart of this Government’s industrial strategy.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-04-24T15:12:49.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722160/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722160/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722160/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-18","Research: South East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to support investment in science research at universities within (a) West Sussex and (b) the South East.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","71072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722161","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>As part of the exit negotiations the Government will discuss with the European Union and Member States how best to continue cooperation in the field of medicines regulation in the best interests of both the United Kingdom and the EU. It would not be appropriate to pre-judge the outcome of the negotiations.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-26T10:22:22.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722161/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722161/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722161/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-18","European Medicines Agency: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on the UK pharmaceuticals industry of the relocation out of the UK of the European Medicines Agency.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","71006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722162","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-24","<p>The future of the European Banking Authority (EBA), and any potential effects on the wider banking sector relating to the location of EBA staff, is subject to the outcome of the withdrawal negotiations.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-04-24T15:33:16.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722162/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722162/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722162/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-04-18","European Banking Authority: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on the UK banking sector of the relocation out of the UK of the European Banking Authority.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","71007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722163","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-20","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy does not hold information on the average salary of mothers or fathers taking Shared Parental Leave.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-04-20T13:48:23.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722163/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722163/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722163/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-18","Parents: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the average salary of (a) mothers and (b) fathers taking shared parental leave is.","false","Biography information for Mr Gavin Shuker","Luton South","Mr Gavin Shuker","71012"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722164","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-26","<p>Since the formation of the Department for International Trade in July, this department has employed 106 full time equivalent third-party contractors and consultants.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-04-26T16:31:20.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722164/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722164/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722164/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-18","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many full-time equivalent third-party contractors and consultants his Department has employed since its establishment; and what the cost to the public purse has been of that employment.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","71028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722165","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Department for International Trade has a strong core of trade policy officials, which has quadrupled in size since 24 June (from 45 to over 200 today) and is continuing to grow. The trade policy team includes policy and country specialists, as well as economic analysts and lawyers.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-04-26T16:35:29.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722165/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722165/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722165/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-18","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many full-time equivalent trade negotiators his Department employed on 31 March 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","71029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722166","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-26","<p>At this stage, the Department’s primary focus is on developing our trade policy positions, international relationships and approach to future trade negotiations.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has run a number of recruitment exercises since July 2016 for both internal Civil Service and external candidates. From these recruitment exercises the Department’s Trade Policy Team has taken on over 150 new members of staff to fill a range of trade policy positions, including analytical and legal posts.</p><p> </p><p>We are also in the process of recruiting a Chief Trade Negotiations Adviser at the level of Second Permanent Secretary.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-04-26T14:41:09.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722166/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722166/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722166/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-18","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many (a) applications, (b) applicants, (c) interviews and (d) job offers there have been for trade negotiator positions in his Department since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","71030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722167","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Department for International Trade has a strong core of trade policy officials, which has quadrupled in size since 24 June (from 45 to over 200) and is continuing to grow. This includes policy and country specialists, as well as economic analysts and lawyers.</p><p> </p><p>At this stage our primary focus is on developing our policy positions, international relationships and approach to future trade negotiations.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-04-25T12:29:47.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722167/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722167/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722167/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-18","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what estimate his Department has made of the number of trade negotiators that will be required to conduct parallel negotiations with the EU, the World Trade Organisation and other nations in the next two years.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","71031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722168","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-24","<p>The UK is Egypt’s largest foreign direct investor and is a longstanding trading partner. To increase trade and investment further, the Department for International Trade (DIT) works with UK companies already in Egypt and supports those exploring the market for the first time. UK Export Finance has increased its country limit to support UK trade with Egypt to £750m and guarantees approved loans to Egyptian buyers denominated in Egyptian Pounds. The Prime Minister’s Trade Envoy, Sir Jeffrey Donaldson, works with DIT to promote UK trade and investment with Egypt. In addition, five UK trade delegations have visited Egypt over the last year.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-04-24T13:55:24.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722168/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722168/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722168/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-18","Overseas Trade: Egypt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps his Department is taking to increase trade with Egypt.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","71022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722169","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-26","<p>The department for International Trade currently employs 106 full time equivalent third-party contractors and consultants, and would expect to employ similar numbers in the future.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-04-26T16:32:31.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722169/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722169/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722169/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-18","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many full-time equivalent third-party contractors and consultants his Department plans to employ in (a) 2017, (b) 2018 and (c) 2019; and what the cost to the taxpayer will be of that employment in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","71033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722170","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Department for International Trade (DIT) does not have a specific number of staff tasked with responding to Freedom of Information (FOI) requests. On receipt, FOI requests are allocated to officials in the area of the Department relevant to the subject of the request, who then provide the response.</p><p>The Department for Business Energy &amp; Industrial Strategy (BEIS), Information Rights Unit (IRU) processes all FOI requests on behalf of DIT and provides advice and assistance to staff on the application of information rights legislation. The IRU consists of eight members of staff.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-04-25T09:15:36.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722170/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722170/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722170/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-18","Department for International Trade: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many staff in his Department respond to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","71047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722171","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-04-27","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union’s FOI team is appropriately staffed to make sure the department meets its statutory obligations. Within the past quarter, we responded to 97% of FOI requests within the 20 working day deadline set by the Information Commissioner's Office. As recruitment to the department is still ongoing we are not in a position to give a final total for particular groups of staff.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-04-27T09:00:22.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722171/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722171/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722171/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-04-18","Department for Exiting the European Union: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many staff in his Department respond to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","71042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722172","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-04-27","<p>The department has sourced a large proportion of experienced staff from across Whitehall and a number of secondees and contractors from the private sector and the wider public sector. We are not in a position to give a final total for particular groups of staff as recruitment is ongoing and numbers are regularly changing. The total cost of consultancy for 2016/17 will be published in the Department’s Annual Report and Accounts in the summer.</p><p>Plans and budgets for third-party contractors and consultants for future years have not been finalised and will be kept under review.</p><p><strong><p><p><br></strong></p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","71027","2017-04-27T08:58:00.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722172/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722172/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722172/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-04-18","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many full-time equivalent third-party contractors and consultants his Department plans to employ in (a) 2017, (b) 2018 and (c) 2019; and what the cost to the taxpayer will be in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","71057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722173","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>This Government intends to secure the best possible outcome for the UK as we exit the European Union. The UK has played a major part in developing the main EU space programmes including Galileo. We would welcome an agreement to continue to collaborate with our European partners on major science, research, and technology initiatives; however it is too early to speculate on the UK’s future relationship with specific EU programmes and the Government will not be providing a commentary on each aspect of the negotiations.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","71078","2017-04-24T15:08:05.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722173/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722173/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722173/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-18","Galileo System","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with EU counterparts on the future participation of the UK-based companies in the Galileo project after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","71079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722174","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>This Government intends to secure the best possible outcome for the UK as we exit the European Union. The UK has played a major part in developing the main EU space programmes including Galileo. We would welcome an agreement to continue to collaborate with our European partners on major science, research, and technology initiatives; however it is too early to speculate on the UK’s future relationship with specific EU programmes and the Government will not be providing a commentary on each aspect of the negotiations.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","71079","2017-04-24T15:08:05.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722174/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722174/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722174/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-18","Galileo System","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with EU counterparts on the continued participation of the UK in the Galileo project after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","71078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722175","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>UK companies have been central to the development of the Galileo satellite navigation system since its inception. While the UK remains a Member of the European Union we will fully participate in the EU space programmes including Galileo, and it is the Government’s position that UK industry should be able to compete fairly for contracts during this period. The Government would welcome an agreement to continue to collaborate with our European partners on major science, research, and technology initiatives however the details of any future relationship will be part of the upcoming negotiations.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-04-24T15:57:36.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722175/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722175/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722175/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-18","Galileo System","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many UK-based companies will potentially be excluded from the Galileo project supply chain after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","71081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722176","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>People and businesses in the UK will be able to continue to use the freely available signals from satellite navigation systems such as the American GPS and Galileo after the UK has left the EU. The UK’s arrangements to access the encrypted GPS signals will be unaffected by UK exit from the EU. upcoming negotiations. The UK is a world leader in the development of applications which exploit the signals from satellite navigation systems.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","71190","2017-04-24T15:10:48.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722176/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722176/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722176/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-18","Global Navigation Satellite Systems","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what navigation system he plans for the UK to use after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","71080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722177","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-04-27","<p>The department has sourced a large proportion of experienced staff from across Whitehall and a number of secondees and contractors from the private sector and the wider public sector. We are not in a position to give a final total for particular groups of staff as recruitment is ongoing and numbers are regularly changing. The total cost of consultancy for 2016/17 will be published in the Department’s Annual Report and Accounts in the summer.</p><p>Plans and budgets for third-party contractors and consultants for future years have not been finalised and will be kept under review.</p><p><strong><p><p><br></strong></p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","71057","2017-04-27T08:58:00.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722177/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722177/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722177/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-04-18","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many full-time equivalent third-party contractors and consultants his Department has employed since its establishment; and what the cost to the taxpayer has been of that employment.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","71027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722178","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-04-27","<p>All costs related to the case have not yet been settled. Details of the total costs associated with the case, including the costs of the Supreme Court appeal, will be published in due course after they have been settled. <br><br></p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-04-27T09:03:53.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722178/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722178/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722178/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-04-18","Department for Exiting the European Union: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 27 January 2017 to Question 61331, what the total cost to his Department was of the court case R (Miller) v the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union in the Supreme Court; and if he will publish to which standard departmental cost headings those costs have been allocated.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","71024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722179","Cabinet Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and therefore is only available at disproportionate cost.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-04-24T15:31:05.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722179/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722179/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/722179/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-04-18","Cabinet Office: Surveys","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what his Department's total expenditure on independent polling was in the financial years (a) 2014-15, (b) 2015-16 and (c) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","71162"
